# Module Experiment 2 — Word Count Program Using MapReduce

## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### Formal Academic Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

The **Word Count Program** is the canonical introductory MapReduce application used to demonstrate parallel distributed processing of large textual datasets. Formally, it is defined as a distributed algorithm that tokenises an unstructured input corpus, emits a (key, value) pair of the form (word, 1) for every occurrence of a token in the **Map phase**, then aggregates these counts per unique word in the **Shuffle, Sort, and Reduce phase** to produce a final (word, total_count) result. The experiment directly maps to **Course Outcome CO1** (Develop MapReduce-based solutions for big data processing) and **CO2** (Configure Hadoop clusters and execute distributed jobs).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Syllabus Highlight:** In the 2024 scheme lab manual, the Word Count problem is the *Hello, World!* of the Big Data Processing Lab (PCCDL607). Mastering it is essential as it forms the base for every subsequent experiment — Inverted Indexing, TF-IDF, and Log Analytics — all of which extend this same skeleton.

### Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Imagine your college is conducting the **SJCET Student Council Election 2025** and you have been appointed as the chief returning officer. You cannot tally votes alone because there are **12,000 ballot slips** spread across **30 polling booths**. So you distribute the work:

1. **Each polling booth volunteer** (think of them as **Mappers**) opens their box, looks at every slip, and writes down entries like `(Candidate_A, 1), (Candidate_B, 1), (Candidate_A, 1)` on a notepad — one for every slip they see.
2. All volunteers then **send their notepads to a central sorting room** (the **Shuffle & Sort** phase), where a clerk groups all entries by candidate name: all `Candidate_A` slips together, all `Candidate_B` slips together.
3. A **head counter** (think of them as the **Reducer**) takes each pile and simply adds up the ones to produce the final tally: `(Candidate_A, 4500), (Candidate_B, 3200)`.

That is **exactly** what MapReduce Word Count does with words instead of candidates.

> [!NOTE]
> **Core Components Required:**
> - **Input:** A plain text file stored on **HDFS** (Hadoop Distributed File System).
> - **Mapper Class:** Extends `org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Mapper`.
> - **Reducer Class:** Extends `org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Reducer`.
> - **Driver Class:** Contains the `main()` method to configure and submit the Hadoop `Job`.
> - **Output:** A part-file in HDFS containing lines of `word\tcount`.
<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference Sheet

### 2.1 MapReduce Execution Pipeline (Word Count Context)

The Hadoop framework divides every MapReduce job into the following structured phases. The bullet points below map each phase to the Word Count domain:

- **Input Split Phase** — Hadoop logically divides the input file into splits of size equal to one **HDFS block** (default **128 MB**). Each split is assigned to one Mapper.
  - *Word Count context:* If `input.txt` is **512 MB**, it yields **4 splits**, hence **4 parallel Mappers** on a 4-node cluster.

- **Map Phase** — Each Mapper processes one (Key, Value) pair at a time where Key = byte offset (LongWritable) and Value = line of text (Text).
  - *Word Count context:* For every line, the Mapper tokenises using whitespace and emits `(word, 1)`.

- **Combine Phase (Optional Optimisation)** — A mini-reducer running on the Mapper node itself to reduce network traffic during the Shuffle phase.
  - *Word Count context:* If a single line has "the the the", the combiner locally aggregates to `(the, 3)` before sending it to the Reducer.

- **Shuffle and Sort Phase** — Framework-level phase where Mapper outputs are partitioned, transferred across the network, sorted by key, and grouped.
  - *Word Count context:* All pairs for the word "hadoop" from every Mapper are routed to the same Reducer.

- **Reduce Phase** — Each Reducer receives `(word, [1, 1, 1, ...])` and sums the iterable values to produce `(word, total_count)`.

- **Output Phase** — The Reducer writes its final (key, value) pairs to HDFS as a `part-r-00000` file.

### 2.2 KTU High-Yield Reference Sheet (Configuration & Class Specifications)

The table below captures every parameter, class, and boundary a KTU examiner expects you to recall during the lab viva and external examination. **Note:** All vertical bar delimiters use `\vert` to remain markdown-safe.

| **Component** | **Class / Constant** | **Specification / Boundary** |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Mapper Base Class | `org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Mapper` | Generics: `<LongWritable, Text, Text, IntWritable>` |
| Reducer Base Class | `org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Reducer` | Generics: `<Text, IntWritable, Text, IntWritable>` |
| Default Block Size | `dfs.blocksize` | **128 MB** (Hadoop 2.x+) |
| Default Replication Factor | `dfs.replication` | **3** copies per block |
| Mapper Output Key Type | `Text` | Stores the tokenised word |
| Mapper Output Value Type | `IntWritable` | Always emitted as **1** |
| Driver Class Job Name | `Job.getInstance(conf, "Word Count")` | Human-readable label for the JobTracker UI |
| Input Format | `TextInputFormat` | Default; reads line-by-line |
| Output Format | `TextOutputFormat` | Default; writes tab-separated `key\tvalue` |
| Tokeniser Regex | `\\s+` (Java String) | One or more whitespace characters |
| Common Port | `localhost:50070` | HDFS Web UI port |
| Job Submission Return | `job.waitForCompletion(true)` | Boolean — true if job succeeded |

### 2.3 Real-World Engineering Utility

The Word Count pattern is the structural backbone of nearly every large-scale text analytics pipeline in industry. Specific applications include:

- **Search Engines** (Google, Bing): Term frequency pre-computation for indexing.
- **Social Media Sentiment Mining:** Counting hashtag usage across billions of tweets.
- **Log Analytics:** Counting ERROR, WARN, INFO occurrences in server logs to detect anomalies.
- **Genomics & Bioinformatics:** Counting k-mers in DNA sequences stored across thousands of files.
- **Cybersecurity:** Identifying the frequency of suspicious tokens in packet capture dumps.
<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
## 3. Step-by-Step Code Walkthrough & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 The Mapper Class — `WordCountMapper.java`

The Mapper reads each line of input, tokenises it on whitespace, and emits a (word, 1) pair for every token. The exhaustive Java implementation is presented below.

```java
// File: WordCountMapper.java
// Package: default package (for academic simplicity; production code uses reverse-DNS naming)
import java.io.IOException;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.IntWritable;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.LongWritable;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.Text;
import org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Mapper;

public class WordCountMapper extends Mapper<LongWritable, Text, Text, IntWritable> {

    // Reusable instance variables — critical for performance.
    // Hadoop reuses Mapper objects across many map() invocations,
    // so allocating new objects inside map() would cause severe GC pressure.
    private final static IntWritable one = new IntWritable(1);
    private Text word = new Text();

    @Override
    protected void map(LongWritable key, Text value, Context context)
            throws IOException, InterruptedException {

        // Step 1: Convert the Hadoop Text value to a standard Java String.
        String line = value.toString();

        // Step 2: Tokenise the line on one-or-more whitespace characters.
        //         The regex \\s+ handles tabs, spaces, multiple spaces uniformly.
        String[] tokens = line.split("\\s+");

        // Step 3: Iterate through every token and emit (word, 1) to the context.
        for (String token : tokens) {
            // Optional sanity check — skip empty strings produced by leading whitespace.
            if (token.length() == 0) {
                continue;
            }
            word.set(token);
            context.write(word, one);
        }
    }
}
```

**Line-by-Line Logic Decomposition:**

1. `extends Mapper<LongWritable, Text, Text, IntWritable>` — The four generic parameters declare: Input Key (`LongWritable` byte offset), Input Value (`Text` line), Output Key (`Text` word), Output Value (`IntWritable` count).
2. `private final static IntWritable one = new IntWritable(1)` — `final static` guarantees a single shared instance. Hadoop Writable objects are mutable; reusing one prevents creating thousands of garbage objects.
3. `context.write(word, one)` — Writes the (word, 1) pair to the Mapper's local output buffer, which is later flushed, partitioned, sorted, and sent to Reducers.

### 3.2 The Reducer Class — `WordCountReducer.java`

The Reducer receives a key (word) and an iterable of values (all the `1`s). It simply sums them.

```java
// File: WordCountReducer.java
import java.io.IOException;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.IntWritable;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.Text;
import org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Reducer;

public class WordCountReducer extends Reducer<Text, IntWritable, Text, IntWritable> {

    @Override
    protected void reduce(Text key, Iterable<IntWritable> values, Context context)
            throws IOException, InterruptedException {

        // Step 1: Initialise the accumulator to zero.
        int sum = 0;

        // Step 2: Iterate through the iterable list of 1s and accumulate.
        //         Note: the Iterable is re-used by Hadoop for memory efficiency,
        //         so we MUST read each value into a local variable (val.get())
        //         rather than caching the IntWritable object itself.
        for (IntWritable val : values) {
            sum += val.get();
        }

        // Step 3: Emit the final (word, total_count) pair to HDFS.
        context.write(key, new IntWritable(sum));
    }
}
```

### 3.3 The Driver Class — `WordCountDriver.java`

The Driver class wires the Mapper, Reducer, and Hadoop configuration together and submits the job to the cluster.

```java
// File: WordCountDriver.java
import org.apache.hadoop.conf.Configuration;
import org.apache.hadoop.fs.Path;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.IntWritable;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.Text;
import org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Job;
import org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.lib.input.FileInputFormat;
import org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.lib.output.FileOutputFormat;

public class WordCountDriver {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

        // Step 1: Create a Hadoop Configuration object.
        //         Configuration reads core-site.xml, mapred-site.xml, hdfs-site.xml.
        Configuration conf = new Configuration();

        // Step 2: Instantiate the Job and assign a human-readable name.
        Job job = Job.getInstance(conf, "Word Count");

        // Step 3: Set the entry-point class so Hadoop can locate the JAR.
        job.setJarByClass(WordCountDriver.class);

        // Step 4: Bind the Mapper and Reducer classes.
        job.setMapperClass(WordCountMapper.class);
        job.setReducerClass(WordCountReducer.class);

        // Step 5: Declare the final output key/value types emitted by the Reducer.
        job.setOutputKeyClass(Text.class);
        job.setOutputValueClass(IntWritable.class);

        // Step 6: Set input directory (from CLI arg[0]) and output directory (arg[1]).
        FileInputFormat.addInputPath(job, new Path(args[0]));
        FileOutputFormat.setOutputPath(job, new Path(args[1]));

        // Step 7: Submit the job and block until completion.
        //         Returns true on success, false on failure.
        boolean isSuccess = job.waitForCompletion(true);

        // Step 8: Exit with status code 0 on success, 1 on failure.
        System.exit(isSuccess ? 0 : 1);
    }
}
```

### 3.4 Compilation, JAR Packaging, and Execution Steps

The full cluster-side workflow — frequently asked in KTU viva and lab records — is enumerated below.

- **Step A — Set HADOOP_CLASSPATH:** Export the path to the Hadoop JARs so `javac` and `java` can find them.

$$
\text{export HADOOP\_CLASSPATH} = \text{\$(hadoop classpath):\$HADOOP\_CLASSPATH}
$$

- **Step B — Compile the Java sources:** Generates `WordCountMapper.class`, `WordCountReducer.class`, `WordCountDriver.class`.

```bash
javac -classpath $(hadoop classpath) -d ./classes WordCountMapper.java WordCountReducer.java WordCountDriver.java
```

- **Step C — Package into a JAR:** Bundles the compiled `.class` files into a single JAR for cluster distribution.

```bash
jar -cvf wordcount.jar -C ./classes .
```

- **Step D — Stage input data on HDFS:** Uploads `input.txt` from local filesystem to the `/input` directory on HDFS.

```bash
hdfs dfs -put ./input.txt /input
hdfs dfs -ls /input
```

- **Step E — Submit the MapReduce job:** Hadoop's `ResourceManager` allocates containers, the `ApplicationMaster` orchestrates execution, and Mappers/Reducers run in parallel.

```bash
hadoop jar wordcount.jar WordCountDriver /input /output_wc
```

- **Step F — Retrieve and view the result:** Output resides in `/output_wc/part-r-00000` on HDFS.

```bash
hdfs dfs -cat /output_wc/part-r-00000
```

- **Step G — Clean HDFS output (for re-runs):** Hadoop refuses to overwrite an existing output directory.

```bash
hdfs dfs -rm -r /output_wc
```
