## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

**Q1. [KTU University Exam — June 2024]** Define the Mapper and Reducer functions used in a MapReduce Word Count program.

**Model Answer:** The **Mapper function** is the user-defined implementation of the `map()` method that processes one input record (Key = byte offset, Value = one line of text) and emits an arbitrary number of intermediate (key, value) pairs. In Word Count, the Mapper tokenises the input line using `line.split("\\s+")` and emits a `(word, 1)` pair for every token. The **Reducer function** is the user-defined implementation of the `reduce()` method that receives a key and an iterable list of all values associated with that key (grouped during the Shuffle phase). For Word Count, the Reducer iterates through the list of `1`s and sums them, emitting a final `(word, total_count)` pair. **(3 marks)**

**Q2. [KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]** What is the role of the Driver class in a Hadoop MapReduce application?

**Model Answer:** The **Driver class** is the entry point of a MapReduce application and contains the `main()` method. Its roles are: (i) instantiating the Hadoop `Configuration` object, (ii) creating a `Job` instance and setting a human-readable job name, (iii) binding the Mapper and Reducer classes via `setMapperClass()` and `setReducerClass()`, (iv) declaring final output key/value types via `setOutputKeyClass()` and `setOutputValueClass()`, (v) specifying the HDFS input and output paths from command-line arguments, and (vi) submitting the job to the cluster using `job.waitForCompletion(true)`. Without the Driver class, Hadoop has no knowledge of which user code to execute. **(3 marks)**

---

### Part B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each, Internal Choice Provided)

#### Question A (14 Marks)

**Q.A. [KTU University Exam — June 2024]** (a) Write and explain the complete MapReduce program for the Word Count problem. (7 marks) (b) Explain the Shuffle and Sort phase in MapReduce with reference to the Word Count example. (7 marks)

**Model Solution:**

**(a) Complete MapReduce Program with Explanation (7 marks):**
The complete solution comprises three Java files: `WordCountMapper.java`, `WordCountReducer.java`, and `WordCountDriver.java`. The **Mapper class** extends `Mapper<LongWritable, Text, Text, IntWritable>`, overrides the `map()` method, converts each input line to a Java `String`, splits it on the regex `\\s+`, and for each non-empty token calls `context.write(word, new IntWritable(1))`. The **Reducer class** extends `Reducer<Text, IntWritable, Text, IntWritable>`, iterates through the `Iterable<IntWritable> values` while accumulating `sum += val.get()`, and finally emits `context.write(key, new IntWritable(sum))`. The **Driver class** configures the `Job`, binds the Mapper/Reducer classes, declares output types (`Text.class`, `IntWritable.class`), sets input/output paths from `args[0]` and `args[1]`, and submits the job via `job.waitForCompletion(true)`. **Detailed code** — refer to Section 3.1, 3.2, and 3.3 of these notes for the complete annotated listings. The program is compiled with `javac -classpath $(hadoop classpath)`, packaged into a JAR, and executed with `hadoop jar wordcount.jar WordCountDriver /input /output`. **(7 marks)**

**(b) Shuffle and Sort Phase Explanation (7 marks):**
The **Shuffle and Sort phase** is a framework-managed, automatic phase that sits between the Map and Reduce stages and is responsible for grouping all Mapper outputs by key. In the Word Count context, after the Mappers emit their local `(word, 1)` pairs to a circular buffer, the framework performs three sub-steps:

1. **Partitioning:** A `Partitioner` (default: `HashPartitioner`) computes `hash(key) mod numReduceTasks` to determine which Reducer each (key, value) pair should go to. All pairs for the same word always map to the same Reducer.
2. **Transfer (Shuffle):** Each Reducer fetches its assigned partition from every Mapper's output across the network. For example, all occurrences of "hadoop" from Mappers 1, 2, and 3 are pulled by Reducer 2.
3. **Sort and Group:** On the Reducer node, the framework sorts the fetched pairs by key lexicographically and groups them into an `Iterable` per unique key. The Reducer's `reduce()` method is then invoked once per unique key with that iterable. **(7 marks)**

---

#### Question B (14 Marks — Alternative Choice)

**Q.B. [KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]** (a) Explain the Mapper and Reducer classes for Word Count with suitable code snippets. (7 marks) (b) List and explain the steps to compile and execute a Word Count MapReduce program on a Hadoop cluster. (7 marks)

**Model Solution:**

**(a) Mapper and Reducer Code Explanation (7 marks):**
The **Mapper** is declared as `public class WordCountMapper extends Mapper<LongWritable, Text, Text, IntWritable>`. It declares two reusable members: `private final static IntWritable one = new IntWritable(1);` and `private Text word = new Text();`. The `map(LongWritable key, Text value, Context context)` method reads `value.toString()`, splits on `\\s+`, and calls `context.write(word, one)` for each token. Reusing `one` as a static is a performance best-practice. The **Reducer** is declared as `public class WordCountReducer extends Reducer<Text, IntWritable, Text, IntWritable>`. Its `reduce(Text key, Iterable<IntWritable> values, Context context)` method maintains an `int sum = 0`, increments it via `sum += val.get();` inside a for-each loop, and finally calls `context.write(key, new IntWritable(sum))`. The four generic type parameters of the Reducer specify (input key, input value, output key, output value). Since both Mapper and Reducer must declare the same output key and value types as the Job configuration, both use `Text` and `IntWritable`. **(7 marks)**

**(b) Compilation and Execution Steps (7 marks):**
**Step 1 — Environment Setup:** Ensure Hadoop is installed and `$HADOOP_HOME` is set. Start HDFS and YARN daemons via `start-dfs.sh` and `start-yarn.sh`.

**Step 2 — Classpath Configuration:** Export the Hadoop classpath for compilation.

$$
\text{export HADOOP\_CLASSPATH} = \text{\$(hadoop classpath)}
$$

**Step 3 — Compilation:** Compile all three Java files into bytecode classes using `javac -classpath $(hadoop classpath) -d ./classes *.java`.

**Step 4 — JAR Packaging:** Bundle the classes into `wordcount.jar` using `jar -cvf wordcount.jar -C ./classes .`.

**Step 5 — HDFS Input Staging:** Upload the local input file using `hdfs dfs -put input.txt /input`.

**Step 6 — Job Submission:** Execute the job with `hadoop jar wordcount.jar WordCountDriver /input /output_wc`. The YARN `ResourceManager` allocates containers and dispatches Map and Reduce tasks.

**Step 7 — Result Verification:** View the output using `hdfs dfs -cat /output_wc/part-r-00000`.

**Step 8 — Cleanup:** Remove the output directory before re-running, since Hadoop will not overwrite it: `hdfs dfs -rm -r /output_wc`. **(7 marks)**

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning — Where Students Commonly Lose Marks:**
> 1. **Forgetting to set `job.setJarByClass()`** — Without it, the cluster cannot locate the Driver and the job fails with `ClassNotFoundException`. **Penalty: 1 mark.**
> 2. **Mismatched generic type parameters** — If Mapper emits `<Text, IntWritable>` but the Job is configured with `setOutputKeyClass(IntWritable.class)`, Hadoop throws a type mismatch error. **Penalty: 2 marks.**
> 3. **Allocating `new IntWritable(1)` inside the `for` loop** — This defeats Hadoop's object reuse optimisation and shows poor understanding of Writable contracts. Examiners deduct **1 mark** even if the code runs.
> 4. **Hardcoding paths instead of using `args[0]` and `args[1]`** — KTU strictly requires command-line argument handling. **Penalty: 1 mark.**
> 5. **Not deleting the output directory between runs** — Word Count will fail with `org.apache.hadoop.mapred.FileAlreadyExistsException`. Examiners expect students to know the `-rm -r` command. **Penalty: 1 mark.**
> 6. **Confusing MapReduce with Spark** — These are distinct frameworks. Examiners will award zero if you write PySpark code in a MapReduce viva.

---

### Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- **Word Count** is the **canonical MapReduce "Hello, World!"** program and forms the base for nearly all distributed text analytics.
- A MapReduce job has **two user-defined classes (Mapper, Reducer)** and **one Driver class** for configuration.
- The Mapper emits **(word, 1)** and the Reducer emits **(word, sum)** — this is the immutable contract of the experiment.
- Hadoop default **block size** is **128 MB** (Hadoop 2.x and above) and **replication factor** is **3**.
- **Writable objects** (`IntWritable`, `Text`, `LongWritable`) are mutable and must be **reused** — never allocate inside hot loops.
- The **Shuffle and Sort phase** is automatic and framework-managed; the user cannot directly intervene except via custom `Partitioner` or `Combiner` classes.
- The four generic type parameters of the Mapper are `<InputKeyType, InputValueType, OutputKeyType, OutputValueType>`.
- Compilation command: `javac -classpath $(hadoop classpath) -d ./classes *.java`.
- Execution command: `hadoop jar wordcount.jar WordCountDriver /input /output_wc`.
- **Always delete** the output directory before re-running: `hdfs dfs -rm -r /output_wc`.
- The default tokeniser regex `\\s+` handles spaces, tabs, and consecutive whitespace uniformly — KTU's preferred standard.
- The **Combiner** (mini-reducer) is optional but strongly recommended for Word Count to reduce network traffic during Shuffle.
- The Web UIs for monitoring jobs are at **`localhost:8088`** (YARN) and **`localhost:50070`** (HDFS).
- **Key industry insight:** Word Count's logical structure underlies **TF-IDF, Inverted Index, Log Mining, and Sentiment Analysis** — all directly testable in higher modules.
<!-- SECTION_5_END -->
